insert into public.concepts
  (id, term, aliases, said, alias_list, status, one_liner, analogy, example, related, deeper, lens_pm, lens_eng, domain, priority, tags)
values
  ('autonomous-agent', 'Autonomous Agent', '', '', ARRAY['autonomous-agent','autonomous agent','fully autonomous agent']::text[], 'Rising', 'An AI system that takes a goal and runs the whole way to done without a human in the loop for each step.', 'A contractor you hand a key and a punch list — they let themselves in, do the work, and call you when it’s finished.', 'You say “file my expenses for the trip,” and it reads the receipts, categorizes them, fills the form, and submits — no clicks from you.', '[{"text":"It’s the agent loop running unsupervised.","id":"agent-loop"},{"text":"The opposite of keeping a person on every step.","id":"hitl"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s the same loop — think, act, observe, repeat — just with the human approvals removed. Autonomy is a dial, not a switch: more autonomy means more speed and less oversight, so the failure modes get bigger too. The honest catch is that a wrong turn early can compound into a very confident, very wrong result before anyone notices.', 'Higher autonomy trades human effort for risk — decide per task how much you’re willing to let it run alone.', 'The control loop iterates without blocking on human approval between actions, bounded only by stop conditions and guardrails.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('semi-autonomous', 'Semi-Autonomous', '', '', ARRAY['semi-autonomous','semi autonomous','human-in-the-loop agent']::text[], 'Rising', 'An agent that does the work on its own but pauses to ask a human before the risky moves.', 'A learner driver — hands on the wheel most of the time, but the instructor grabs it before anything expensive happens.', 'The coding agent writes and tests the fix by itself, then stops and asks “push to main?” before it actually deploys.', '[{"text":"The checkpoint where it waits for a yes.","id":"approval-gate"},{"text":"Keeping a person on the consequential calls.","id":"hitl"},{"text":"Sits between manual and fully unsupervised.","id":"autonomous-agent"}]'::jsonb, 'The design question is where to put the gates — too many and it’s just a slow assistant, too few and it’s effectively autonomous. Good semi-autonomous systems reserve the human for irreversible or high-cost actions and let the agent own everything cheap and undoable. It’s the pragmatic middle most production agents actually live in.', 'You get most of the speed of autonomy while keeping veto power over the moves that can hurt.', 'The loop inserts a blocking approval step before actions flagged as high-risk or irreversible.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-framework', 'Agent Framework', '', '', ARRAY['agent-framework','agent framework','agent library']::text[], 'Rising', 'A toolkit that gives you the scaffolding — loops, tools, memory — so you’re not building an agent from scratch.', 'A kitchen that comes with the stove, counters, and knives already installed — you bring the recipe, not the plumbing.', 'A team picks a framework like LangGraph or the Agents SDK so they can wire up tools and a loop in an afternoon instead of a month.', '[{"text":"The environment the framework actually runs in.","id":"agent-runtime"},{"text":"The repeating cycle the framework manages for you.","id":"agent-loop"}]'::jsonb, 'Frameworks bundle the boring-but-necessary parts: calling the model, parsing tool calls, tracking state, retrying failures. The tradeoff is abstraction — they save you time until the day their assumptions don’t match yours and you’re fighting the framework instead of the problem. Many mature teams eventually rip theirs out for something thinner.', 'Frameworks buy speed early; weigh that against being locked into someone else’s idea of how agents should work.', 'It abstracts the model-call, tool-dispatch, and state-management loop behind a higher-level API.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-runtime', 'Agent Runtime', '', '', ARRAY['agent-runtime','agent runtime','execution runtime']::text[], 'Rising', 'The live environment that actually runs the agent — holding its state, executing its tools, and keeping the loop turning.', 'The engine bay under the hood — you don’t look at it, but it’s where the running actually happens.', 'When the deployed agent handles a support ticket, the runtime is the process spinning up its tools, tracking the conversation, and enforcing the token budget.', '[{"text":"The framework defines it; the runtime runs it.","id":"agent-framework"},{"text":"What the runtime keeps between steps.","id":"agent-state"}]'::jsonb, 'The framework is the design-time toolkit; the runtime is the thing executing in production, managing concurrency, timeouts, and resource limits. A weak runtime is where agents that looked great in a demo fall over — leaked memory, stuck loops, tools that hang. It’s the unglamorous layer that decides whether your agent is reliable at scale.', 'Demo quality and production quality diverge here — the runtime is where reliability is won or lost.', 'It manages process lifecycle, concurrency, resource limits, and tool execution for a running agent.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-harness', 'Agent Harness', '', '', ARRAY['agent-harness','agent harness','scaffolding']::text[], 'Rising', 'The wrapper of code around the model that turns raw text prediction into an agent that can actually do things.', 'A climbing harness — the rope, clips, and straps that let a capable climber attempt something they couldn’t do bare-handed.', 'The same model gets 20% on a coding benchmark with a bare prompt and 60% once you put it in a good harness that lets it run tests and read errors.', '[{"text":"The harness runs the think-act-observe cycle.","id":"agent-loop"},{"text":"How much of the score is model vs. scaffolding.","id":"agent-evaluation"}]'::jsonb, 'A model on its own only predicts text; the harness is what gives it tools, feeds back results, and lets it retry. A surprising amount of “model progress” on agent benchmarks is really harness progress — better scaffolding around the same weights. That makes it hard to compare models fairly, since a strong harness can flatter a weak model.', 'When comparing agent results, ask how much is the model and how much is the scaffolding around it.', 'The harness supplies tool interfaces, feedback loops, and retry logic that wrap the base model into an agent.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('looping', 'Looping', '', '', ARRAY['looping','agent looping','stuck in a loop']::text[], 'Rising', 'When an agent gets stuck repeating the same step, never making progress toward done.', 'A GPS that keeps rerouting you around the same block, confidently, forever.', 'The agent tries a broken command, reads the error, tries the exact same command again, reads the same error — and does it forty times until something stops it.', '[{"text":"The rule that finally breaks the cycle.","id":"stop-condition"},{"text":"The hard cap that ends a runaway loop.","id":"max-iterations"}]'::jsonb, 'Looping usually happens when the agent can’t tell that its last action failed, or has no new information to act on, so it just re-derives the same plan. It’s the classic agent failure mode and the reason you never run a loop without a ceiling. Fixes range from clearer tool errors to nudging the agent to try something different after a repeat.', 'An agent with no loop ceiling can quietly burn a fortune in tokens doing nothing — always cap it.', 'The agent re-emits equivalent actions because the observation doesn’t change its state enough to alter the next decision.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('stop-condition', 'Stop Condition', '', '', ARRAY['stop-condition','stop condition','termination condition']::text[], 'Rising', 'The rule that tells an agent it’s done — or that it should quit trying.', 'The timer on the oven — it doesn’t decide the food is perfect, it just decides when to stop cooking.', 'The agent stops when the task returns “success,” when it hits ten steps, or when it says the magic phrase that means “I’m finished.”', '[{"text":"The blunt version — a hard step cap.","id":"max-iterations"},{"text":"What it prevents when things go wrong.","id":"looping"}]'::jsonb, 'Every agent loop needs a way out, and there are usually several: task success, an explicit “done” signal from the model, a step or token ceiling, or an error the agent can’t recover from. The tricky part is a stop that fires too early (gives up on solvable work) or too late (keeps flailing). Good stop conditions blend a success test with a safety cap.', 'Where you set the stop line decides the balance between giving up too soon and wasting money too long.', 'A predicate evaluated each iteration — success, explicit termination, resource ceiling, or unrecoverable error.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('max-iterations', 'Max Iterations', '', '', ARRAY['max-iterations','max iterations','iteration cap','step limit']::text[], 'Rising', 'A hard cap on how many times an agent can loop before you pull the plug.', 'A prepaid phone — when the minutes run out, the call ends whether or not you were finished.', 'You set max iterations to 25 so that a confused agent stops after 25 steps instead of spinning through your entire budget.', '[{"text":"The blunt safety net under every loop.","id":"stop-condition"},{"text":"What it exists to stop.","id":"looping"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s the least clever but most important safeguard — a plain counter that guarantees termination no matter how badly the agent is stuck. Set it too low and you cut off genuinely long tasks; too high and a broken agent still runs up the bill. It pairs with smarter stop conditions rather than replacing them: the cap is the floor, the success test is the goal.', 'It’s the cheapest insurance against a runaway agent — set it before anything ships.', 'A monotonic step counter that forces loop exit once it exceeds a fixed threshold.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-evaluation', 'Agent Evaluation', '', '', ARRAY['agent-evaluation','agent evaluation','agent evals']::text[], 'Rising', 'Measuring whether an agent actually completes real tasks, not just whether the model sounds smart.', 'A road test, not a written exam — it doesn’t matter what the driver can recite if they can’t park the car.', 'You run the agent against 200 recorded support tickets and score how many it resolved end-to-end without a human stepping in.', '[{"text":"The general practice of scoring model output.","id":"evals"},{"text":"Separating model skill from scaffolding.","id":"agent-harness"}]'::jsonb, 'Evaluating agents is harder than evaluating a single answer because success is a whole trajectory — many steps, tool calls, and side effects — and there’s often more than one right path. You care about task completion, cost, and safety, not just whether the final text looks good. The messy truth is that reliable agent evals are still an open problem, and a lot of reported numbers are fragile.', 'A demo proves an agent can work once; evaluation tells you how often it works — insist on the second.', 'Score full trajectories on task success, cost, and safety across a fixed benchmark of scenarios.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('tool-registry', 'Tool Registry', '', '', ARRAY['tool-registry','tool registry','tool catalog']::text[], 'Rising', 'The catalog of tools an agent is allowed to use, each with a description of what it does and how to call it.', 'A restaurant menu — the agent can only order what’s printed, and each item comes with a description.', 'The registry lists send_email, search_web, and query_database, so the agent knows those three exist and exactly what arguments each one takes.', '[{"text":"Each entry is defined by its schema.","id":"tool-schema"},{"text":"How an agent finds out what’s on the menu.","id":"capability-discovery"}]'::jsonb, 'The registry is both a menu and a fence: it tells the agent what’s available and, by omission, what isn’t. Descriptions matter enormously — a vague tool description means the agent picks the wrong tool or mangles the arguments. As registries grow past a few dozen tools, the model starts to struggle to choose, which is why big toolsets get grouped or filtered before they reach the prompt.', 'What’s in the registry defines what your agent can and can’t do — it’s a product decision, not just plumbing.', 'A lookup of available tools with their schemas and descriptions, injected into or filtered before the model context.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('capability-discovery', 'Capability Discovery', '', '', ARRAY['capability-discovery','capability discovery','tool discovery']::text[], 'Rising', 'How an agent finds out at runtime what tools and abilities are available to it.', 'Walking into a new workshop and reading the labels on the drawers before you start a job.', 'On connecting to an MCP server, the agent asks “what can you do?” and gets back a live list of tools it can call.', '[{"text":"The menu it discovers.","id":"tool-registry"},{"text":"The protocol that made dynamic discovery common.","id":"mcp"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of hard-coding a fixed tool list, discovery lets an agent query its environment and adapt to whatever’s connected. This is a big part of why protocols like MCP took off — plug in a new server and the agent just sees the new tools. The catch is that more discoverable tools means more choices to get wrong, so discovery usually pairs with filtering to keep the active set manageable.', 'Discovery is what lets one agent work across many tools without a code change for each — it’s the extensibility story.', 'The agent queries connected servers or a registry at runtime to enumerate available tools and their schemas.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('permissions', 'Permissions', '', '', ARRAY['permissions','agent permissions']::text[], 'Core', 'The rules that decide which actions an agent is allowed to take and which it isn’t.', 'A hotel keycard — it opens your room and the gym, but not the manager’s office.', 'The agent can read your calendar and draft emails, but it needs a separate permission before it’s allowed to actually send one.', '[{"text":"Narrowing permissions to just what’s needed.","id":"scoped-access"},{"text":"The pause where a person grants a one-off permission.","id":"approval-gate"}]'::jsonb, 'Permissions are the difference between a helpful agent and a dangerous one, because the same system that can send an email can also delete a database. The safe default is least privilege — grant only what the task needs, and require explicit approval for anything irreversible. As agents act more autonomously, permissioning stops being a checkbox and becomes the core safety mechanism.', 'Decide up front what an agent may touch — permissions are where you draw the line between useful and reckless.', 'An access-control layer that gates each action against a policy before it executes.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('scoped-access', 'Scoped Access', '', '', ARRAY['scoped-access','scoped access','least privilege']::text[], 'Core', 'Giving an agent the narrowest set of permissions that still lets it finish the job.', 'Handing a house-sitter the key to the front door and the alarm code — not the safe, the car, and your bank login.', 'A summarizing agent gets read-only access to one folder, not write access to the whole drive, so a bug can’t delete anything.', '[{"text":"The broader system this narrows.","id":"permissions"},{"text":"Fences that keep it inside its lane.","id":"agent-guardrails"}]'::jsonb, 'Scoping is the principle of least privilege applied to agents: minimize the blast radius if something goes wrong or gets hijacked. It matters more for agents than for ordinary software because a prompt-injected agent will happily use whatever access it has. Good scoping is granular — per-tool, per-resource, per-task — rather than one big “can do everything” grant.', 'Narrow access limits how much damage a confused or compromised agent can do — scope tightly by default.', 'Grant per-resource, per-action tokens so a compromised agent’s reach is bounded to the task at hand.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-guardrails', 'Agent Guardrails', '', '', ARRAY['agent-guardrails','agent guardrails','guardrails']::text[], 'Rising', 'The checks and limits that keep an agent inside safe behavior even when it wants to wander.', 'The rails on a bowling lane — the ball can still curve, but it can’t end up in the neighbor’s gutter.', 'A guardrail blocks the agent from ever calling the “delete customer” tool, and flags any output containing a credit card number before it’s sent.', '[{"text":"One kind of guardrail — limiting what it can reach.","id":"scoped-access"},{"text":"A human-approval guardrail on risky moves.","id":"approval-gate"}]'::jsonb, 'Guardrails wrap the agent with independent checks — input filters, output validation, banned actions, rate limits — that don’t rely on the model behaving well. The key idea is that they sit outside the model, so a jailbroken or confused agent still hits the wall. They’re never perfect, and over-tight guardrails make agents useless, so the craft is blocking the catastrophic without smothering the helpful.', 'Guardrails are what let you deploy an agent you don’t fully trust — invest in them before autonomy, not after.', 'Independent pre- and post-checks around the model that validate inputs, outputs, and actions regardless of model behavior.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('delegation', 'Delegation', '', '', ARRAY['delegation','task delegation']::text[], 'Rising', 'When one agent hands a piece of work to another agent better suited to do it.', 'A GP referring you to a specialist instead of trying to do the surgery themselves.', 'The main agent hits a math-heavy step, so it delegates that part to a dedicated calculation agent and waits for the answer.', '[{"text":"A common shape delegation takes.","id":"manager-worker"},{"text":"Passing control to another agent.","id":"handoff"},{"text":"Breaking work up so it can be handed off.","id":"task-decomposition"}]'::jsonb, 'Delegation lets you compose specialists instead of building one agent that does everything mediocrely. It introduces the same overhead any org has — briefing the other party, trusting their result, reconciling it back. The failure mode is a game of telephone where context gets lost at each handoff, so good delegation is careful about what information travels with the task.', 'Delegation lets you assemble focused agents into a capable whole, at the cost of coordination overhead.', 'One agent invokes another as a sub-call, passing a scoped task and integrating its returned result.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('manager-worker', 'Manager-Worker', '', '', ARRAY['manager-worker','manager worker','supervisor-worker','orchestrator-worker']::text[], 'Rising', 'A multi-agent setup where one agent plans and delegates while others do the actual tasks.', 'A head chef calling out orders while the line cooks each handle their station.', 'A manager agent breaks “research these five companies” into five jobs and hands one to each worker, then stitches their findings together.', '[{"text":"The act of handing work down.","id":"delegation"},{"text":"Coordinating the whole team.","id":"orchestration"},{"text":"A flatter alternative with no boss.","id":"swarm"}]'::jsonb, 'This is the most common multi-agent pattern because it mirrors how human teams work: one planner, several doers. It parallelizes cleanly and keeps each worker’s context small and focused. The cost is that the manager becomes the bottleneck and single point of failure — if it plans badly, the whole team executes the wrong thing efficiently.', 'It’s the natural shape for splitting big jobs, but the manager’s judgment gates the whole team’s output.', 'A supervisor agent decomposes and dispatches subtasks to worker agents, then aggregates their results.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('swarm', 'Swarm', '', '', ARRAY['swarm','agent swarm','swarm of agents']::text[], 'Rising', 'A group of agents that coordinate as peers, with no single boss directing them.', 'A flock of birds turning together — no lead bird, just simple local rules that add up to a shape.', 'A dozen small agents each explore a different part of a codebase and share what they find on a common board until the bug is located.', '[{"text":"The top-down alternative with a boss.","id":"manager-worker"},{"text":"The shared space peers write to.","id":"blackboard"},{"text":"Many agents in general.","id":"multi-agent"}]'::jsonb, 'Swarms trade central control for resilience and parallelism — no manager to bottleneck or crash, but also no one holding the overall plan. Coordination happens through shared state or messages rather than commands. They can be powerful for search-like problems but are notoriously hard to steer and debug, since behavior emerges from the interactions rather than living in one place.', 'Swarms shine on parallel exploration but are hard to predict and control — use them where breadth beats precision.', 'Peer agents coordinate via shared state or message-passing without a central controller.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('blackboard', 'Blackboard', '', '', ARRAY['blackboard','blackboard pattern','shared workspace']::text[], 'Rising', 'A shared space where multiple agents post partial results and read each other’s work.', 'A whiteboard in a war room — everyone scribbles findings on it and glances up to see what others added.', 'Three research agents each write their notes to a common blackboard, and a fourth agent reads the whole board to write the final summary.', '[{"text":"The memory the board is made of.","id":"shared-memory"},{"text":"A pattern swarms often use to coordinate.","id":"swarm"}]'::jsonb, 'The blackboard is an old AI idea reborn for agents: instead of agents messaging each other directly, they all read and write one common store. It decouples them — an agent doesn’t need to know who will use its output, just where to put it. The risk is contention and staleness: agents acting on half-finished notes, or overwriting each other, unless you’re careful about how the board is structured.', 'A blackboard lets agents collaborate without tight wiring, but shared scratch space needs structure to stay useful.', 'A shared read/write store agents post intermediate results to, decoupling producers from consumers.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('shared-memory', 'Shared Memory', '', '', ARRAY['shared-memory','shared memory','shared context']::text[], 'Rising', 'A common store that several agents can all read from and write to.', 'A shared kitchen fridge — everyone in the house can take from it and add to it.', 'A team of agents keeps its running findings in one shared store, so a worker that starts later can see what earlier ones already learned.', '[{"text":"A structured way to use shared memory.","id":"blackboard"},{"text":"The multi-agent setups that rely on it.","id":"multi-agent"}]'::jsonb, 'Shared memory is how multi-agent systems avoid re-doing each other’s work, but it brings all the classic problems of shared state: race conditions, stale reads, and one agent clobbering another’s entry. You trade the simplicity of isolated agents for the efficiency of pooled knowledge. In practice it needs conventions — who writes where, how conflicts resolve — or it turns into a mess fast.', 'Pooled memory makes agent teams more efficient but adds the coordination costs of anything shared.', 'A concurrently accessed store across agents, subject to consistency and contention concerns.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('episodic-memory', 'Episodic Memory', '', '', ARRAY['episodic-memory','episodic memory']::text[], 'Rising', 'An agent’s record of specific past events — what happened, when, and how it turned out.', 'A diary — not general knowledge, but “on Tuesday I tried X and it failed.”', 'The agent remembers that last time it used a certain API it got rate-limited, so this time it slows down its calls.', '[{"text":"The fast, in-the-moment counterpart.","id":"working-memory"},{"text":"Pulling the right past episode back up.","id":"memory-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Borrowed from psychology, episodic memory is about particular experiences rather than facts — a log of trajectories the agent can learn from. It lets an agent avoid repeating mistakes and reuse past solutions, but it also grows without bound, so you need retrieval to surface the relevant episode instead of dumping the whole history. Deciding what’s worth remembering is the hard part.', 'Episodic memory is how an agent gets better with use instead of starting fresh every time.', 'A store of past interaction traces, keyed for retrieval so relevant episodes can inform future decisions.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('working-memory', 'Working Memory', '', '', ARRAY['working-memory','working memory','scratch memory']::text[], 'Rising', 'The small, fast scratch space an agent uses to hold what it’s thinking about right now.', 'The sticky notes on your desk during a task — grabbed, glanced at, and tossed when you’re done.', 'While booking a trip, the agent keeps the current dates, budget, and shortlisted flights in working memory, not in long-term storage.', '[{"text":"The durable counterpart for lasting facts.","id":"episodic-memory"},{"text":"Where working memory physically lives for an LLM.","id":"contextwindow"},{"text":"A place to jot intermediate thinking.","id":"scratchpad"}]'::jsonb, 'For an LLM agent, working memory usually is the context window — the live set of tokens it’s reasoning over. It’s fast but tiny and volatile: once it fills or the task ends, that content is gone unless it’s written somewhere durable. The whole discipline of context management exists because working memory is scarce and precious.', 'Working memory is limited, so what an agent can juggle at once is a real constraint on task complexity.', 'The active context the model reasons over each step — fast, capacity-bounded, and non-persistent.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('memory-retrieval', 'Memory Retrieval', '', '', ARRAY['memory-retrieval','memory retrieval']::text[], 'Rising', 'Pulling the right past information back into an agent’s working memory when it’s relevant.', 'Remembering a friend’s allergy right as you’re about to order for the table — the fact surfaces when you need it.', 'Before answering, the agent retrieves the note it saved three sessions ago that this user prefers metric units.', '[{"text":"The durable events it retrieves from.","id":"episodic-memory"},{"text":"The general technique it borrows from.","id":"retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'An agent can store far more than fits in its context, so retrieval is the bridge — search the memory store and pull only what matters into the prompt. It usually reuses the same machinery as RAG: embeddings, similarity search, ranking. The quality ceiling is the retrieval step: if the right memory isn’t surfaced, it might as well not exist, and irrelevant memories just crowd out useful context.', 'An agent’s memory is only as good as its ability to recall the right piece at the right moment.', 'Query the memory store — usually by embedding similarity — and inject the top matches into the active context.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('context-management', 'Context Management', '', '', ARRAY['context-management','context management','context engineering']::text[], 'Rising', 'The art of deciding what to keep, drop, and summarize so an agent’s limited context stays useful.', 'Packing a carry-on — you can’t bring everything, so you choose what earns its space and leave the rest.', 'As a long agent run fills up, older tool outputs get summarized into a few lines to make room for the current step.', '[{"text":"The scarce space being managed.","id":"contextwindow"},{"text":"Deciding what to pull back in.","id":"memory-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Context is finite and every token costs money and attention, so managing it is one of the central crafts of building agents. Tactics include summarizing old turns, evicting stale tool results, and retrieving only what’s relevant instead of stuffing everything in. Get it wrong and the agent either forgets crucial facts or drowns in noise — and models notably struggle to use the middle of a very full context anyway.', 'Context management is where a lot of agent quality and cost is quietly decided — it deserves real attention.', 'Actively curate the context window each step: summarize, evict, and retrieve to fit the budget without losing signal.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-persona', 'Agent Persona', '', '', ARRAY['agent-persona','agent persona','agent role']::text[], 'Rising', 'The defined character and expertise you give an agent to shape how it behaves.', 'Casting an actor for a part — “you’re a meticulous accountant” gets a different performance than “you’re a brainstorming buddy.”', 'One agent is set up as a skeptical code reviewer and another as an eager junior dev, so together they catch more than either would alone.', '[{"text":"Assigning personas across a team.","id":"role-assignment"},{"text":"Where the persona is usually declared.","id":"systemmessage"}]'::jsonb, 'A persona is usually just a system prompt that fixes the agent’s role, tone, and priorities. It genuinely changes behavior — a “careful reviewer” persona flags issues a neutral one skips — which is powerful and a little unsettling, since it’s all steered by a paragraph of text. The risk is over-believing the costume: a persona shapes style and emphasis, not actual competence.', 'Personas are a cheap, strong lever on agent behavior — but they change how it acts, not what it truly knows.', 'A system-prompt-level specification of role, tone, and priorities that conditions the model’s behavior.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('role-assignment', 'Role Assignment', '', '', ARRAY['role-assignment','role assignment']::text[], 'Rising', 'Giving each agent in a team a distinct job so they don’t all do the same thing.', 'A relay team — someone runs the first leg, someone the last; nobody runs all four.', 'In a writing crew, one agent is assigned to draft, one to fact-check, and one to edit, and work flows between them.', '[{"text":"The character each role wears.","id":"agent-persona"},{"text":"The team structures roles slot into.","id":"multi-agent"},{"text":"Handing the baton between roles.","id":"handoff"}]'::jsonb, 'Role assignment is how multi-agent systems get division of labor: clear responsibilities reduce overlap and keep each agent’s context focused on its slice. Done well, specialists outperform one generalist. Done poorly, you get diffusion of responsibility — every agent assumes another handled the thing, and it falls through the cracks, just like on human teams.', 'Clear roles make an agent team more than the sum of its parts; fuzzy ones make work fall through the cracks.', 'Assign disjoint responsibilities across agents to reduce overlap and bound each one’s context.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('task-queue', 'Task Queue', '', '', ARRAY['task-queue','task queue','work queue']::text[], 'Core', 'A waiting line of jobs for agents to pick up and work through one at a time.', 'The ticket-number system at a deli — jobs get served in order as someone becomes free.', 'Incoming support tickets land in a queue, and whichever agent worker is idle grabs the next one to handle.', '[{"text":"A pattern that feeds work into the queue.","id":"manager-worker"},{"text":"The loop that pulls jobs off it.","id":"event-loop"}]'::jsonb, 'A task queue decouples producing work from doing it, which is what lets you scale agents horizontally — add more workers to drain a deep queue. It also gives you natural retry and prioritization points. The classic pitfalls are the same as any queue: jobs that never finish, poison items that crash every worker, and backlogs that grow faster than you can clear them.', 'Queues are how you smooth bursty demand and scale agent throughput without dropping work on the floor.', 'A buffer decoupling job producers from agent consumers, enabling parallelism, retries, and prioritization.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('event-loop', 'Event Loop', '', '', ARRAY['event-loop','event loop']::text[], 'Core', 'The core cycle that waits for something to happen and then reacts to it, over and over.', 'A receptionist who sits at the desk, and every time the phone rings or someone walks in, handles it, then goes back to waiting.', 'The agent’s event loop waits for a tool result, processes it, decides the next action, fires it, and returns to waiting.', '[{"text":"The agent-specific version of this cycle.","id":"agent-loop"},{"text":"A source of events it reacts to.","id":"task-queue"}]'::jsonb, 'The event loop is a foundational programming pattern — one thread that dispatches work as events arrive instead of blocking on each one. For agents it’s the heartbeat: receive an observation, run the model, dispatch an action, repeat. Understanding it matters because a blocked or stalled loop is a hung agent, and long-running tool calls have to be handled without freezing the whole thing.', 'It’s the agent’s heartbeat — if it stalls, the agent silently stops responding.', 'A single dispatch cycle that processes events (observations, tool results) as they arrive without blocking.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('function-schema', 'Function Schema', '', '', ARRAY['function-schema','function schema']::text[], 'Core', 'The formal description of a function’s name, inputs, and types that tells the model how to call it correctly.', 'A form with labeled, required fields — the model can only fill in what the form asks for, in the right format.', 'The schema says get_weather takes a city string and an optional units field, so the model produces exactly those arguments and nothing else.', '[{"text":"What the schema enables.","id":"function-calling"},{"text":"A near-synonym at the tool level.","id":"tool-schema"},{"text":"The format schemas are usually written in.","id":"json-schema-tools"}]'::jsonb, 'A schema turns a vague “call the weather tool” into a strict contract — required fields, types, allowed values — that the model’s output must satisfy. Good schemas with clear descriptions dramatically cut malformed calls; sloppy ones invite the model to hallucinate arguments. It’s the interface layer where natural language meets structured code, and its quality quietly determines how reliable your tool use is.', 'Well-written schemas are the difference between tools that just work and tools the agent constantly misuses.', 'A typed signature (often JSON Schema) constraining the arguments the model must emit for a tool call.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('json-schema-tools', 'JSON Schema Tools', '', '', ARRAY['json-schema-tools','json schema tools','json schema']::text[], 'Core', 'Describing an agent’s tools using JSON Schema, the standard way to spell out what valid inputs look like.', 'A blank tax form with strict rules — this box is a number, that one’s a date, this one’s required.', 'A tool is defined with a JSON Schema saying its “amount” must be a number and its “currency” must be one of USD, EUR, or GBP.', '[{"text":"The general concept it implements.","id":"function-schema"},{"text":"What it makes reliable.","id":"function-calling"}]'::jsonb, 'JSON Schema is a widely-adopted standard for describing the shape of JSON data — types, required fields, enums, nesting — and it became the lingua franca for defining LLM tools. Providers use it to constrain and sometimes to hard-enforce the model’s output, so a call either matches the schema or is rejected. The upside is interoperability; the friction is that expressive schemas get verbose, and every token spent describing tools is context you don’t get back.', 'Standardizing on JSON Schema means your tool definitions work across models and frameworks instead of being bespoke.', 'Tool inputs are specified as JSON Schema, letting the runtime validate or constrain the model’s emitted arguments.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('parallel-tool-calls', 'Parallel Tool Calls', '', '', ARRAY['parallel-tool-calls','parallel tool calls','parallel function calling']::text[], 'Rising', 'When an agent fires off several independent tool calls at once instead of one after another.', 'Ordering the appetizer, main, and dessert all at once instead of waiting to finish each before asking for the next.', 'Asked to compare three products, the agent looks all three up simultaneously rather than sequentially, cutting the wait to a third.', '[{"text":"The single-call version.","id":"tool-calling"},{"text":"Chaining calls when they do depend on each other.","id":"tool-chaining"}]'::jsonb, 'When tasks don’t depend on each other, running them in parallel is a big latency win — the model emits multiple calls in one turn and the runtime executes them together. The catch is that many tasks are actually dependent (you need result A to know what to look up for B), and the model doesn’t always tell the difference, so it sometimes parallelizes things it shouldn’t. Handling partial failures across the batch adds complexity too.', 'Parallel calls make agents feel much faster on independent work — but only when the steps truly don’t depend on each other.', 'The model emits multiple tool calls in one turn; the runtime dispatches them concurrently and joins the results.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('tool-error-handling', 'Tool Error Handling', '', '', ARRAY['tool-error-handling','tool error handling']::text[], 'Rising', 'What an agent does when a tool call fails — and whether it recovers gracefully or falls apart.', 'A cook whose oven dies mid-service — do they adapt and finish, or stand there staring at it?', 'The database tool times out, so the agent reads the error, waits a moment, and retries once before trying a different approach.', '[{"text":"A common recovery strategy.","id":"retry-logic"},{"text":"Switching to a backup when a tool keeps failing.","id":"fallback-tool"},{"text":"What a stuck agent does instead of recovering.","id":"looping"}]'::jsonb, 'Tools fail constantly — timeouts, bad inputs, rate limits — and how the error is surfaced to the model decides whether it recovers. A clear, structured error (“missing required field: date”) lets the agent fix and retry; a raw stack trace or silent failure sends it into confusion or a loop. Robust agents treat errors as information to act on, not dead ends, which means the error messages themselves become part of the design.', 'Real tools fail often; how the agent handles those failures is most of what separates a demo from production.', 'Surface tool failures as structured, actionable observations so the model can correct rather than loop or stall.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('retry-logic', 'Retry Logic', '', '', ARRAY['retry-logic','retry logic','retries']::text[], 'Core', 'Automatically trying a failed action again, usually with a short pause, in case it was a fluke.', 'Redialing a call that dropped — often it just goes through the second time.', 'A rate-limited API call is retried after waiting two seconds, then four, then eight, before the agent gives up.', '[{"text":"The broader problem it addresses.","id":"tool-error-handling"},{"text":"What to try when retries keep failing.","id":"fallback-tool"}]'::jsonb, 'Many failures are transient — a blip, a momentary rate limit — so retrying with increasing backoff resolves them without bothering anyone. The danger is retrying things that aren’t transient (a genuinely bad request) forever, or hammering a struggling service and making it worse. Sensible retry logic caps the attempts, backs off between them, and knows which errors are worth retrying versus which are hopeless.', 'Retries quietly absorb the flakiness of the real world, but blind retrying can turn a small outage into a big one.', 'Re-attempt transient failures with capped, backoff-spaced retries, distinguishing retryable from terminal errors.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('fallback-tool', 'Fallback Tool', '', '', ARRAY['fallback-tool','fallback tool','backup tool']::text[], 'Rising', 'A backup an agent switches to when its first-choice tool fails or isn’t available.', 'Taking the stairs when the elevator’s out — slower, but you still get up.', 'The premium search API is down, so the agent falls back to a basic web search to keep the task moving.', '[{"text":"What triggers reaching for a fallback.","id":"tool-error-handling"},{"text":"The retries that come first.","id":"retry-logic"}]'::jsonb, 'Fallbacks add resilience by giving the agent a plan B when a tool is broken, throttled, or missing. The tradeoff is usually quality or cost — the backup is cheaper, slower, or less capable — so you accept a worse result over no result. The subtle risk is silent degradation: the agent quietly downgrades and nobody realizes the answers got worse until it matters.', 'Fallbacks keep agents working through outages, but watch for silent quality drops when the backup kicks in.', 'On primary-tool failure, route to an alternate tool with equivalent intent but different cost or capability.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-observability', 'Agent Observability', '', '', ARRAY['agent-observability','agent observability','agent monitoring']::text[], 'Rising', 'Being able to see what an agent actually did — every step, tool call, and decision — after the fact.', 'A flight recorder — when something goes wrong, you can replay exactly what happened and why.', 'When an agent gives a bad answer, you open its trace and see it retrieved the wrong document three steps back.', '[{"text":"The full record of a single run.","id":"trace"},{"text":"One step within a trace.","id":"span"},{"text":"The per-step record it depends on.","id":"step-logging"}]'::jsonb, 'Agents are non-deterministic and multi-step, so “it gave a weird answer” is useless without the ability to inspect the whole run. Observability means capturing traces, tool inputs and outputs, timings, and costs so you can debug and improve. It’s harder than logging normal software because the interesting failures are in the model’s reasoning, which you can only see indirectly through what it chose to do.', 'Without observability you can’t tell why an agent failed — it’s the prerequisite for ever making it better.', 'Capture structured traces of every step, tool I/O, latency, and cost to enable debugging and evaluation.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('trace', 'Trace', '', '', ARRAY['trace','execution trace','agent trace']::text[], 'Core', 'The complete step-by-step record of a single agent run, from the request to the final answer.', 'A hiking log with every turn and rest stop marked — the whole route, not just the destination.', 'The trace shows the agent’s five steps: read the ticket, search docs, draft a reply, check policy, send.', '[{"text":"What traces make possible.","id":"agent-observability"},{"text":"The individual steps inside a trace.","id":"span"}]'::jsonb, 'A trace is the top-level container for everything that happened in one run — a tree of steps, each with its inputs, outputs, and timing. It’s the primary unit you inspect when debugging and the raw material for evaluation. The concept comes straight from distributed-systems tracing, adapted to the reality that an agent’s “request” fans out into many model calls and tool invocations.', 'The trace is the story of one run — the first thing to open when something went wrong.', 'A tree of spans capturing the full execution of one agent invocation, end to end.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('span', 'Span', '', '', ARRAY['span','trace span']::text[], 'Core', 'A single timed step inside a trace — one model call or tool invocation with its inputs and outputs.', 'One line item on an itemized receipt — this thing, this long, this cost.', 'Within the trace, one span is the “search docs” tool call: it took 400ms, took this query, returned these three results.', '[{"text":"The whole run a span belongs to.","id":"trace"},{"text":"What spans add up to enable.","id":"agent-observability"}]'::jsonb, 'Spans are the building blocks of a trace — each captures one unit of work with a start, end, and metadata, and spans nest to show what called what. They’re where you find the actual detail: the exact prompt sent, the tokens used, the tool’s raw response. Borrowed from distributed tracing, the span/trace pair is what lets you zoom from “the whole run” down to “this one slow call.”', 'Spans are the zoom-in — where you see the specific step that cost the most time or money.', 'A single timed, attributed unit of work within a trace, nestable to reflect call hierarchy.', 'Agents & tools', 80, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('step-logging', 'Step Logging', '', '', ARRAY['step-logging','step logging','action logging']::text[], 'Rising', 'Recording each thing an agent does as it does it, so there’s a paper trail of the whole run.', 'A ship’s logbook — each event written down as it happens, not reconstructed later from memory.', 'Every time the agent picks a tool, the log captures which one, with what arguments, and what came back.', '[{"text":"What step logs roll up into.","id":"trace"},{"text":"The discipline they support.","id":"agent-observability"}]'::jsonb, 'Step logging is the low-level habit that makes observability possible: write down each action, thought, and result at the moment it occurs. Without it, a failed run is a black box. The tension is verbosity versus signal — log too little and you can’t debug, log everything and you drown in noise and storage cost. Structured logs that you can query beat walls of raw text.', 'Cheap discipline now, huge payoff later — you can only debug what you bothered to log.', 'Emit a structured record per agent action (thought, tool call, result) as it executes, feeding traces.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('cost-tracking', 'Cost Tracking', '', '', ARRAY['cost-tracking','cost tracking','spend tracking']::text[], 'Rising', 'Keeping tabs on how much money and tokens an agent burns, per run and in total.', 'Watching the meter in a taxi — you want to know the fare is climbing before you arrive, not after.', 'A dashboard shows that one customer’s agent runs average 40,000 tokens each, flagging the one that spiked to 500,000.', '[{"text":"The ceiling you set once you know the costs.","id":"token-budget"},{"text":"Where per-step costs get recorded.","id":"step-logging"}]'::jsonb, 'Agents can be shockingly expensive because a single task fans out into many model calls, and a looping agent can 10x its own cost silently. Tracking spend per run, per user, and per tool is how you catch that before the bill does. It also surfaces which steps are worth optimizing — often one wasteful retrieval or an over-stuffed context is most of the cost, and you’d never know without measuring.', 'Agent economics can make or break a feature — you can’t price or optimize what you don’t measure.', 'Attribute token and dollar cost per step, run, and user to catch runaway spend and target optimization.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('token-budget', 'Token Budget', '', '', ARRAY['token-budget','token budget','token limit per run']::text[], 'Rising', 'A cap on how many tokens an agent may spend on a task before it has to stop or economize.', 'A daily allowance — once it’s gone, you either wrap up or do the rest more cheaply.', 'A run is given a 200,000-token budget, and as it approaches the limit the agent starts summarizing instead of keeping full history.', '[{"text":"How you know what budget to set.","id":"cost-tracking"},{"text":"A budget-driven stop.","id":"stop-condition"},{"text":"The scarce space budgets are spent on.","id":"contextwindow"}]'::jsonb, 'A token budget is both a cost control and a forcing function: knowing it’s finite pushes the agent (and its designer) to spend context wisely. It ties directly to stop conditions — hit the budget and the run ends or degrades gracefully. The design question is what happens at the limit: hard stop, summarize-and-continue, or ask a human, each with a different tradeoff between completeness and cost.', 'Budgets keep agent costs predictable and force hard choices about what’s worth spending context on.', 'A per-run token ceiling that triggers summarization, degradation, or termination as it’s approached.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('agent-orchestrator', 'Agent Orchestrator', '', '', ARRAY['agent-orchestrator','agent orchestrator','orchestrator']::text[], 'Rising', 'The controller that coordinates multiple agents and tools, deciding who does what and when.', 'A conductor — not playing an instrument, but keeping every section in time and on cue.', 'The orchestrator receives a request, routes the research part to one agent and the writing part to another, then assembles the result.', '[{"text":"The general act it performs.","id":"orchestration"},{"text":"A common structure it manages.","id":"manager-worker"},{"text":"The engine that runs defined flows.","id":"workflow-engine"}]'::jsonb, 'The orchestrator is the brain of a multi-agent system — it holds the overall plan, dispatches work, and reconciles results, so the individual agents can stay simple and focused. It can be itself an LLM making dynamic decisions or a fixed program running a defined flow. Its judgment gates the whole system, and it’s the natural single point of failure, so it tends to get the most design scrutiny.', 'The orchestrator’s decisions shape the whole system’s behavior — it’s where you invest the most design care.', 'A coordinating layer that routes tasks among agents and tools and integrates their outputs, dynamically or via fixed flow.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('workflow-engine', 'Workflow Engine', '', '', ARRAY['workflow-engine','workflow engine']::text[], 'Rising', 'A system that runs a defined sequence of steps reliably, handling ordering, retries, and failures.', 'An assembly line — each station does its part in order, and if one jams, the line knows how to respond.', 'A workflow engine runs “extract → validate → summarize → email” for every uploaded document, retrying any step that fails.', '[{"text":"A fixed flow it typically runs.","id":"deterministic-workflow"},{"text":"The flexible counterpart it can also drive.","id":"dynamic-workflow"},{"text":"The LLM-driven coordinator it contrasts with.","id":"agent-orchestrator"}]'::jsonb, 'Workflow engines predate LLMs — they’re the durable backbone for multi-step processes, guaranteeing steps run in order, survive crashes, and resume where they left off. For AI systems they’re increasingly paired with agents: the engine handles the reliable plumbing while the model handles the judgment. The tradeoff is rigidity — engines love predictable flows and chafe against the open-ended improvisation agents are good at.', 'Use an engine when a process must run reliably every time; use an agent when it needs to improvise.', 'A durable executor that sequences steps with ordering, retry, and crash-recovery guarantees.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('deterministic-workflow', 'Deterministic Workflow', '', '', ARRAY['deterministic-workflow','deterministic workflow','fixed workflow']::text[], 'Rising', 'A process where the steps are fixed in advance, so the same input follows the same path every time.', 'A recipe followed exactly — same ingredients, same steps, same cake, every single time.', 'Every invoice runs the identical path: parse, check totals, match to a PO, then route for approval — no improvising.', '[{"text":"The open-ended opposite.","id":"dynamic-workflow"},{"text":"The engine that runs fixed flows.","id":"workflow-engine"}]'::jsonb, 'When you know the steps ahead of time, hard-coding them is more reliable, cheaper, and easier to test than letting a model decide each move. You often still use an LLM inside a step (to extract or classify) while the flow itself stays fixed. The limit is obvious: deterministic flows can’t handle situations you didn’t anticipate, so they suit well-understood processes, not open-ended tasks.', 'For predictable, high-volume processes, a fixed flow beats an agent on cost, reliability, and testability.', 'The control flow is statically defined; models may fill steps, but the path between steps is fixed.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('dynamic-workflow', 'Dynamic Workflow', '', '', ARRAY['dynamic-workflow','dynamic workflow','agentic workflow']::text[], 'Rising', 'A process where an agent decides the next step at runtime instead of following a fixed path.', 'Improvising a road trip — you pick each turn based on what you find, rather than following a printed itinerary.', 'Given a research question, the agent chooses whether to search, read, calculate, or ask a follow-up, and the path differs every time.', '[{"text":"The fixed-path opposite.","id":"deterministic-workflow"},{"text":"The loop that makes it dynamic.","id":"agent-loop"},{"text":"The controller often driving it.","id":"agent-orchestrator"}]'::jsonb, 'Dynamic workflows trade predictability for flexibility: the model chooses each step, so the system can handle situations no one scripted. That’s exactly what makes agents powerful and exactly what makes them hard to test, budget, and trust. The mature pattern is a blend — a deterministic skeleton for the parts you understand, with dynamic decision-making reserved for the genuinely open-ended steps.', 'Dynamic flows handle the unexpected but cost you predictability — reserve them for where flexibility truly earns its keep.', 'The model selects each next action at runtime, so the execution path is decided dynamically rather than predefined.', 'Agents & tools', 60, ARRAY['seed','agents-tools']::text[]),
  ('semantic-search', 'Semantic Search', '', '', ARRAY['semantic-search','semantic search','meaning-based search']::text[], 'Core', 'Search that matches on meaning rather than exact words, so “car” can find “automobile.”', 'A helpful librarian who understands what you’re after, not a card catalog that only matches the exact title.', 'You search “how do I cancel my plan” and it finds the doc titled “Ending your subscription,” despite zero shared keywords.', '[{"text":"What powers meaning-based matching.","id":"embeddings"},{"text":"The word-matching approach it complements.","id":"bm25"},{"text":"Combining both approaches.","id":"hybrid-search"}]'::jsonb, 'Semantic search turns both the query and the documents into embeddings and finds the ones closest in meaning-space, so it catches paraphrases and synonyms that keyword search misses. The flip side is that it can miss exact matches — a specific error code or product name — because those are about the literal string, not the vibe. That weakness is exactly why it’s so often paired with keyword search.', 'Semantic search makes finding things feel intuitive, but it can fumble exact terms — rarely the whole answer alone.', 'Embed query and documents, then rank by vector similarity in the embedding space.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('similarity-search', 'Similarity Search', '', '', ARRAY['similarity-search','similarity search','nearest neighbor search']::text[], 'Core', 'Finding the items whose vectors are closest to a query’s vector — the engine under semantic search.', 'Finding the nearest coffee shops to your location — sort everything by distance, take the closest few.', 'The query becomes a vector, and the system returns the ten stored vectors sitting nearest to it in the space.', '[{"text":"The user-facing feature it powers.","id":"semantic-search"},{"text":"The structure that makes it fast.","id":"vector-index"},{"text":"What gets compared.","id":"embeddings"}]'::jsonb, 'Similarity search is the mechanical core: given a query vector, find the nearest stored vectors by a distance measure like cosine or dot product. Done naively it means comparing against every vector, which is too slow at scale, so real systems use indexes that trade a little accuracy for huge speed. It’s the same operation whether you call the result semantic search, recommendations, or memory retrieval.', 'It’s the shared engine behind semantic search, recommendations, and agent memory — one primitive, many features.', 'Return the k nearest vectors to a query under a distance metric, usually via an approximate index for speed.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('hybrid-search', 'Hybrid Search', '', '', ARRAY['hybrid-search','hybrid search']::text[], 'Core', 'Combining meaning-based and keyword-based search so you catch both paraphrases and exact terms.', 'Using both a librarian who gets the gist and the card catalog that nails exact titles — and merging their picks.', 'A search for “error 429 rate limit” uses keywords to nail the exact code and semantics to find related throttling docs, then blends the two lists.', '[{"text":"The meaning-based half.","id":"semantic-search"},{"text":"The keyword half.","id":"bm25"},{"text":"A common way to merge the two lists.","id":"reranking"}]'::jsonb, 'Hybrid search runs both a semantic and a keyword retriever and fuses their results, covering each other’s blind spots — semantics for synonyms and intent, keywords for exact strings like names, codes, and jargon. The tricky part is the fusion: how to weight and merge two differently-scaled ranked lists, often with a method like reciprocal rank fusion or a reranker on top. It’s become the default for serious retrieval because neither approach wins alone.', 'Hybrid search is the reliable default — it covers the exact-match cases pure semantic search quietly drops.', 'Run dense and sparse retrievers in parallel and fuse their ranked lists, often via RRF or a reranker.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('bm25', 'BM25', '', '', ARRAY['bm25','okapi bm25','keyword ranking']::text[], 'Core', 'A classic keyword-ranking formula that scores documents by how well their words match the query.', 'A smart word-counter — rewards documents that use your rare search terms often, but doesn’t double-count common filler.', 'Searching “quarterly revenue Anthropic,” BM25 ranks highest the docs that use those exact, uncommon words most.', '[{"text":"The meaning-based approach it’s paired with.","id":"semantic-search"},{"text":"Where it’s combined with vectors.","id":"hybrid-search"}]'::jsonb, 'BM25 is decades old and still a workhorse: it scores on term frequency (how often a query word appears) balanced against how rare that word is overall and how long the document is. It’s fast, needs no training, and is unbeatable at matching exact terms — names, codes, jargon — which is precisely where embeddings struggle. That durability is why nearly every hybrid search still has BM25 doing the keyword half.', 'The old keyword approach still beats fancy embeddings on exact terms — don’t retire it, combine with it.', 'A sparse ranking function scoring on term frequency, inverse document frequency, and length normalization.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('top-k-retrieval', 'Top-K Retrieval', '', '', ARRAY['top-k-retrieval','top-k retrieval','top k retrieval']::text[], 'Core', 'Grabbing the k best-matching chunks for a query — where k is how many you decide to pull.', 'Asking for the top five recommendations, not the entire ranked list of everything.', 'With k set to 5, a question retrieves the five most relevant document chunks to stuff into the prompt.', '[{"text":"How the matches are ranked.","id":"similarity-search"},{"text":"What the retrieved chunks feed.","id":"rag"},{"text":"Cleaning up the top-k before use.","id":"reranking"}]'::jsonb, 'K is one of the most consequential knobs in retrieval: too small and you miss the chunk with the answer, too large and you flood the context with noise and cost. There’s no universal right number — it depends on chunk size, model context, and how scattered the answer is. Because raw top-k by similarity is often imperfect, teams frequently over-retrieve and then rerank down to the truly best few.', 'K trades recall against noise and cost — tuning it is one of the cheapest wins in a retrieval system.', 'Return the k highest-scoring items from the retriever, k being a tunable recall-versus-noise parameter.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('embedding-model', 'Embedding Model', '', '', ARRAY['embedding-model','embedding model','embedder']::text[], 'Core', 'The model whose whole job is to turn text into vectors that place similar meanings close together.', 'A translator that renders every sentence into the same universal coordinate system, so closeness means similarity.', 'You run all your support docs through an embedding model once, store the vectors, and reuse them for every future search.', '[{"text":"The vectors it produces.","id":"embeddings"},{"text":"What those vectors get searched by.","id":"similarity-search"},{"text":"The system it feeds.","id":"rag"}]'::jsonb, 'An embedding model is trained so that texts with similar meaning land near each other in vector space and unrelated ones land far apart. It’s usually separate from and smaller than the generation model, and its quality sets the ceiling for any retrieval built on it — a weak embedder means poor matches no matter how good everything downstream is. Choosing one involves tradeoffs of accuracy, vector size, speed, and language coverage.', 'The embedding model quietly caps the quality of every search and RAG feature built on top of it — choose deliberately.', 'A model mapping text to fixed-length vectors trained so semantic similarity corresponds to vector proximity.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('vector-index', 'Vector Index', '', '', ARRAY['vector-index','vector index']::text[], 'Core', 'A data structure that makes finding the nearest vectors fast, even among millions of them.', 'A library’s shelving system — you don’t walk past every book, the organization takes you near the right shelf instantly.', 'With ten million embeddings, a vector index returns the closest matches in milliseconds instead of scanning them all.', '[{"text":"The operation it accelerates.","id":"similarity-search"},{"text":"The store it lives inside.","id":"vectordatabase"},{"text":"What it organizes.","id":"embeddings"}]'::jsonb, 'Comparing a query against every stored vector is fine for thousands but hopeless for millions, so a vector index organizes the vectors to skip most comparisons. The catch is that fast indexes are usually approximate — they trade a small chance of missing the true nearest neighbor for enormous speed. Tuning that accuracy-versus-speed dial, and the memory the index consumes, is the core operational concern of any vector system.', 'The index is what keeps search fast as your data grows — and the accuracy-versus-speed tradeoff behind it is a real choice.', 'A structure (e.g. HNSW, IVF) enabling sublinear approximate nearest-neighbor search over a vector set.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[])
